import java.security.MessageDigest;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            String text = "Hello world";

         MessageDigest md = MessageDigest.getInstance("SHA-1");
            md.update(text.getBytes());

            byte[] digest = md.digest();
           StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();

          for (byte b : digest) {
              sb.append(String.format("%02x", b));
            }

            System.out.println("Text : " + text);
            System.out.println("SHA-1 Digest : " + sb.toString());
        }
        catch (Exception e) {
            System.out.println("Error: " + e);
        }
    }
}










// 1. Small Definition

SHA-1 (Secure Hash Algorithm 1) is a cryptographic hash function that takes any input message and produces a 160-bit hash (40-hex characters).
It is used for data integrity, though it is now considered weak due to collision attacks.


---

2. Small Algorithm (Steps)

1. Pad the message so that its length becomes 448 mod 512.


2. Append 64-bit length of the original message → total size becomes a multiple of 512 bits.


3. Initialize five 32-bit registers:

H0, H1, H2, H3, H4



4. Divide padded message into 512-bit blocks.


5. For each block:

Break into 16 words of 32 bits each.

Expand them to 80 words using bitwise operations.

Perform 80 rounds using:

Logical functions

Left circular shifts

Round constants

Modular addition


Update H0–H4.



6. After all blocks are processed, concatenate H0 + H1 + H2 + H3 + H4 →
160-bit SHA-1 hash.
